You can use the `when` method to specify the bindings for specific interfaces. Here is an example of how you can modify your code to achieve this:
```
namespace App\Infrastructure\Providers;

class AppServiceProvider extends ServiceProvider
{
    public array $bindings = [
        //... other bindings...
    ];

    public function register(): void
    {
        $this->app->when(function ($app) {
            return $app->bound(IFriendshipService::class);
        })->bind(IFriendshipService::class, FriendNotifier::class);

        $this->app->when(function ($app) {
            return $app->bound(IAuthService::class);
        })->bind(IAuthService::class, AuthNotifier::class);
    }

    //...
}
```
In this example, the `when` method is used to specify a condition under which the binding should be applied. The condition is a closure that returns a boolean value indicating whether the binding should be applied.

In the first case, the condition checks if the `IFriendshipService` interface is bound to an instance. If it is, then the `FriendNotifier` class is bound to `IFriendshipService`.

In the second case, the condition checks if the `IAuthService` interface is bound to an instance. If it is, then the `AuthNotifier` class is bound to `IAuthService`.

This way, `FriendshipService` will only receive a instance of `FriendNotifier`, and `AuthService` will only receive a instance of `AuthNotifier`.

Note that you need to have already registered the interfaces (`IFriendshipService` and `IAuthService`) in the container before you can use the `when` method. You can do this by adding them to the `$bindings` array or by using the `bind` method in the `register` method. For example:
```
public function register(): void
{
    $this->app->bind(IFriendshipService::class);
    $this->app->bind(IAuthService::class);
    //...
}
```
Make sure to register the interfaces before you use the `when` method, otherwise you will get an error.

